Consider the following two code segments. Assume that variables x and y have been declared as int variables and have been assigned integer values.

I.

int result = 0;

if (x > y)

{

result = x - y;

System.out.print(result);

}

else if (x < y)

{

result = y - x;

System.out.print(result);

}

In this code segment, the value of "result" is initially set to 0. Then, an if statement checks if the value of "x" is greater than the value of "y". If this condition is true, the value of "result" is updated to be the difference between "x" and "y". The value of "result" is then printed.

If the condition in the if statement is false, an else if statement checks if the value of "x" is less than the value of "y". If this condition is true, the value of "result" is updated to be the difference between "y" and "x". The value of "result" is then printed.

So, in this code segment, either the difference between "x" and "y" or the difference between "y" and "x" will be calculated and printed, depending on which value is greater.

II.

int result = x * y;

if (result > 50)

{

System.out.print("Result is greater than 50");

}

else if (result < 50)

{

System.out.print("Result is less than 50");

}

else

{

System.out.print("Result is equal to 50");

}

